A Comparison of Methods for Predicting the Geoelectric Field

Introduction

In this work, we compare several methods for specifying the surface geoelectric field given measurements of the surface geomagnetic field. 

Method 1: A surface impedance computed from a pre-existing 1-D model of conductivity, $\sigma$ versus depth, $d$

\begin{equation}
Z_{xy}(\omega) = Z_{yx}(\omega) = f(\sigma(d),d,\omega)
\end{equation}

where the function $f$ involves the use Wait's recursion formula (Wait [1954]; see also formula 2.33 of Simpson and Bahr 2005). E_x and E_y are computed using

\begin{equation}
E_x(\omega) = Z_xy(\omega)B_y(\omega} 
E_y(\omega) = Z_yx(\omega)B_x(\omega} 
\end{equation}

Method 2: Using $\mathbf{E}$ and $\mathbf{B}$ measurements and solving for $Z_{xy}$ and $Z_{yx}$ in

\begin{equation}
E_x(\omega) = Z_{xy}(\omega)B_{y}(\omega)
E_y(\omega) = Z_{yx}(\omega)B_{x}(\omega)
\end{equation}

and linear least squares regression (Sims 1971; Simpson and Bahr 2005).

Method 3: Using $\mathbf{E}$ and $\mathbf{B}$ measurements and solving for $H_{xy}$ and $H_{yx}$ in

E_x(t) = \Delta_{xy} + \sum_{\tau=-Na+1}^{Nc}H_{xy}{t-\tau}B_{y}(t)
E_y(t) = \Delta_{yx} + \sum_{\tau=-Na+1}^{Nc}H_{xy}(t-\tau)B_{x}()

using linear least squares regression, where $Na$ and $Nc$ are the number of acausal and causal terms respectively.  

Method 4: Using $\mathbf{E}$ and $\mathbf{B}$ measurements and solving for $\mathbf{Z}$ in

\end{equation}
\mathbf{E(\omega)} = \mathbf{Z(\omega)}\mathbf{B(\omega)} 
\end{equation}

where $\mathbf{B} = (B_x,B_y)^T, $\mathbf{E} = (E_x,E_y)^T, and

\mathbf{Z} = 
\begin{bmatrix}
Z_xx & Z_yx
Z_xy & Z_yy
\end{bmatrix}

using using linear least squares regression (Sims 1971; Simpson and Bahr 2005).

Method 5: Same as method 3 except instead of linear least squares regression, a robust regression method and an auxiliary remote reference measurements to reduce bias is used (Egbert and Booker, 1986; Chave and Thompson 1989).




